18Jb 1:1 In the land of Uz there lived a man whose name was Job. This man was blameless and upright; he feared God and shunned evil.
18Jb 1:2 He had seven sons and three daughters,
18Jb 1:3 and he owned seven thousand sheep, three thousand camels, five hundred yoke of oxen and five hundred donkeys, and had a large number of servants. He was the greatest man among all the people of the East.
18Jb 1:4 His sons used to take turns holding feasts in their homes, and they would invite their three sisters to eat and drink with them.
18Jb 1:5 When a period of feasting had run its course, Job would send and have them purified. Early in the morning he would sacrifice a burnt offering for each of them, thinking, "Perhaps my children have sinned and cursed God in their hearts." This was Job's regular custom.
18Jb 1:6 One day the angels came to present themselves before the LORD, and Satan also came with them.
18Jb 1:7 The LORD said to Satan, "Where have you come from?" Satan answered the LORD, "From roaming through the earth and going back and forth in it."
18Jb 1:8 Then the LORD said to Satan, "Have you considered my servant Job? There is no one on earth like him; he is blameless and upright, a man who fears God and shuns evil."
18Jb 1:9 "Does Job fear God for nothing?" Satan replied.
18Jb 1:10 "Have you not put a hedge around him and his household and everything he has? You have blessed the work of his hands, so that his flocks and herds are spread throughout the land.
18Jb 1:11 But stretch out your hand and strike everything he has, and he will surely curse you to your face."
18Jb 1:12 The LORD said to Satan, "Very well, then, everything he has is in your hands, but on the man himself do not lay a finger." Then Satan went out from the presence of the LORD.
18Jb 1:13 One day when Job's sons and daughters were feasting and drinking wine at the oldest brother's house,
18Jb 1:14 a messenger came to Job and said, "The oxen were plowing and the donkeys were grazing nearby,
18Jb 1:15 and the Sabeans attacked and carried them off. They put the servants to the sword, and I am the only one who has escaped to tell you!"
18Jb 1:16 While he was still speaking, another messenger came and said, "The fire of God fell from the sky and burned up the sheep and the servants, and I am the only one who has escaped to tell you!"
18Jb 1:17 While he was still speaking, another messenger came and said, "The Chaldeans formed three raiding parties and swept down on your camels and carried them off. They put the servants to the sword, and I am the only one who has escaped to tell you!"
18Jb 1:18 While he was still speaking, yet another messenger came and said, "Your sons and daughters were feasting and drinking wine at the oldest brother's house,
18Jb 1:19 when suddenly a mighty wind swept in from the desert and struck the four corners of the house. It collapsed on them and they are dead, and I am the only one who has escaped to tell you!"
18Jb 1:20 At this, Job got up and tore his robe and shaved his head. Then he fell to the ground in worship
18Jb 1:21 and said£º "Naked I came from my mother's womb, and naked I will depart. The LORD gave and the LORD has taken away; may the name of the LORD be praised."
18Jb 1:22 In all this, Job did not sin by charging God with wrongdoing.
18Jb 2:1 On another day the angels came to present themselves before the LORD, and Satan also came with them to present himself before him.
18Jb 2:2 And the LORD said to Satan, "Where have you come from?" Satan answered the LORD, "From roaming through the earth and going back and forth in it."
18Jb 2:3 Then the LORD said to Satan, "Have you considered my servant Job? There is no one on earth like him; he is blameless and upright, a man who fears God and shuns evil. And he still maintains his integrity, though you incited me against him to ruin him without any reason."
18Jb 2:4 "Skin for skin!" Satan replied. "A man will give all he has for his own life.
18Jb 2:5 But stretch out your hand and strike his flesh and bones, and he will surely curse you to your face."
18Jb 2:6 The LORD said to Satan, "Very well, then, he is in your hands; but you must spare his life."
18Jb 2:7 So Satan went out from the presence of the LORD and afflicted Job with painful sores from the soles of his feet to the top of his head.
18Jb 2:8 Then Job took a piece of broken pottery and scraped himself with it as he sat among the ashes.
18Jb 2:9 His wife said to him, "Are you still holding on to your integrity? Curse God and die!"
18Jb 2:10 He replied, "You are talking like a foolish woman. Shall we accept good from God, and not trouble?" In all this, Job did not sin in what he said.
18Jb 2:11 When Job's three friends, Eliphaz the Temanite, Bildad the Shuhite and Zophar the Naamathite, heard about all the troubles that had come upon him, they set out from their homes and met together by agreement to go and sympathize with him and comfort him.
18Jb 2:12 When they saw him from a distance, they could hardly recognize him; they began to weep aloud, and they tore their robes and sprinkled dust on their heads.
18Jb 2:13 Then they sat on the ground with him for seven days and seven nights. No one said a word to him, because they saw how great his suffering was.
18Jb 3:1 After this, Job opened his mouth and cursed the day of his birth.
18Jb 3:2 He said£º
18Jb 3:3 "May the day of my birth perish, and the night it was said, 'A boy is born!'
18Jb 3:4 That day--may it turn to darkness; may God above not care about it; may no light shine upon it.
18Jb 3:5 May darkness and deep shadow claim it once more; may a cloud settle over it; may blackness overwhelm its light.
18Jb 3:6 That night--may thick darkness seize it; may it not be included among the days of the year nor be entered in any of the months.
18Jb 3:7 May that night be barren; may no shout of joy be heard in it.
18Jb 3:8 May those who curse days curse that day, those who are ready to rouse Leviathan.
18Jb 3:9 May its morning stars become dark; may it wait for daylight in vain and not see the first rays of dawn,
18Jb 3:10 for it did not shut the doors of the womb on me to hide trouble from my eyes.
18Jb 3:11 "Why did I not perish at birth, and die as I came from the womb?
18Jb 3:12 Why were there knees to receive me and breasts that I might be nursed?
18Jb 3:13 For now I would be lying down in peace; I would be asleep and at rest
18Jb 3:14 with kings and counselors of the earth, who built for themselves places now lying in ruins,
18Jb 3:15 with rulers who had gold, who filled their houses with silver.
18Jb 3:16 Or why was I not hidden in the ground like a stillborn child, like an infant who never saw the light of day?
18Jb 3:17 There the wicked cease from turmoil, and there the weary are at rest.
18Jb 3:18 Captives also enjoy their ease; they no longer hear the slave driver's shout.
18Jb 3:19 The small and the great are there, and the slave is freed from his master.
18Jb 3:20 "Why is light given to those in misery, and life to the bitter of soul,
18Jb 3:21 to those who long for death that does not come, who search for it more than for hidden treasure,
18Jb 3:22 who are filled with gladness and rejoice when they reach the grave?
18Jb 3:23 Why is life given to a man whose way is hidden, whom God has hedged in?
18Jb 3:24 For sighing comes to me instead of food; my groans pour out like water.
18Jb 3:25 What I feared has come upon me; what I dreaded has happened to me.
18Jb 3:26 I have no peace, no quietness; I have no rest, but only turmoil."
18Jb 4:1 Then Eliphaz the Temanite replied£º
18Jb 4:2 "If someone ventures a word with you, will you be impatient? But who can keep from speaking?
18Jb 4:3 Think how you have instructed many, how you have strengthened feeble hands.
18Jb 4:4 Your words have supported those who stumbled; you have strengthened faltering knees.
18Jb 4:5 But now trouble comes to you, and you are discouraged; it strikes you, and you are dismayed.
18Jb 4:6 Should not your piety be your confidence and your blameless ways your hope?
18Jb 4:7 "Consider now£º Who, being innocent, has ever perished? Where were the upright ever destroyed?
18Jb 4:8 As I have observed, those who plow evil and those who sow trouble reap it.
18Jb 4:9 At the breath of God they are destroyed; at the blast of his anger they perish.
18Jb 4:10 The lions may roar and growl, yet the teeth of the great lions are broken.
18Jb 4:11 The lion perishes for lack of prey, and the cubs of the lioness are scattered.
18Jb 4:12 "A word was secretly brought to me, my ears caught a whisper of it.
18Jb 4:13 Amid disquieting dreams in the night, when deep sleep falls on men,
18Jb 4:14 fear and trembling seized me and made all my bones shake.
18Jb 4:15 A spirit glided past my face, and the hair on my body stood on end.
18Jb 4:16 It stopped, but I could not tell what it was. A form stood before my eyes, and I heard a hushed voice£º
18Jb 4:17 'Can a mortal be more righteous than God? Can a man be more pure than his Maker?
18Jb 4:18 If God places no trust in his servants, if he charges his angels with error,
18Jb 4:19 how much more those who live in houses of clay, whose foundations are in the dust, who are crushed more readily than a moth!
18Jb 4:20 Between dawn and dusk they are broken to pieces; unnoticed, they perish forever.
18Jb 4:21 Are not the cords of their tent pulled up, so that they die without wisdom?'
18Jb 5:1 "Call if you will, but who will answer you? To which of the holy ones will you turn?
18Jb 5:2 Resentment kills a fool, and envy slays the simple.
18Jb 5:3 I myself have seen a fool taking root, but suddenly his house was cursed.
18Jb 5:4 His children are far from safety, crushed in court without a defender.
18Jb 5:5 The hungry consume his harvest, taking it even from among thorns, and the thirsty pant after his wealth.
18Jb 5:6 For hardship does not spring from the soil, nor does trouble sprout from the ground.
18Jb 5:7 Yet man is born to trouble as surely as sparks fly upward.
18Jb 5:8 "But if it were I, I would appeal to God; I would lay my cause before him.
18Jb 5:9 He performs wonders that cannot be fathomed, miracles that cannot be counted.
18Jb 5:10 He bestows rain on the earth; he sends water upon the countryside.
18Jb 5:11 The lowly he sets on high, and those who mourn are lifted to safety.
18Jb 5:12 He thwarts the plans of the crafty, so that their hands achieve no success.
18Jb 5:13 He catches the wise in their craftiness, and the schemes of the wily are swept away.
18Jb 5:14 Darkness comes upon them in the daytime; at noon they grope as in the night.
18Jb 5:15 He saves the needy from the sword in their mouth; he saves them from the clutches of the powerful.
18Jb 5:16 So the poor have hope, and injustice shuts its mouth.
18Jb 5:17 "Blessed is the man whom God corrects; so do not despise the discipline of the Almighty.
18Jb 5:18 For he wounds, but he also binds up; he injures, but his hands also heal.
18Jb 5:19 From six calamities he will rescue you; in seven no harm will befall you.
18Jb 5:20 In famine he will ransom you from death, and in battle from the stroke of the sword.
18Jb 5:21 You will be protected from the lash of the tongue, and need not fear when destruction comes.
18Jb 5:22 You will laugh at destruction and famine, and need not fear the beasts of the earth.
18Jb 5:23 For you will have a covenant with the stones of the field, and the wild animals will be at peace with you.
18Jb 5:24 You will know that your tent is secure; you will take stock of your property and find nothing missing.
18Jb 5:25 You will know that your children will be many, and your descendants like the grass of the earth.
18Jb 5:26 You will come to the grave in full vigor, like sheaves gathered in season.
18Jb 5:27 "We have examined this, and it is true. So hear it and apply it to yourself."
18Jb 6:1 Then Job replied£º
18Jb 6:2 "If only my anguish could be weighed and all my misery be placed on the scales!
18Jb 6:3 It would surely outweigh the sand of the seas--no wonder my words have been impetuous.
18Jb 6:4 The arrows of the Almighty are in me, my spirit drinks in their poison; God's terrors are marshaled against me.
18Jb 6:5 Does a wild donkey bray when it has grass, or an ox bellow when it has fodder?
18Jb 6:6 Is tasteless food eaten without salt, or is there flavor in the white of an egg?
18Jb 6:7 I refuse to touch it; such food makes me ill.
18Jb 6:8 "Oh, that I might have my request, that God would grant what I hope for,
18Jb 6:9 that God would be willing to crush me, to let loose his hand and cut me off!
18Jb 6:10 Then I would still have this consolation--my joy in unrelenting pain--that I had not denied the words of the Holy One.
18Jb 6:11 "What strength do I have, that I should still hope? What prospects, that I should be patient?
18Jb 6:12 Do I have the strength of stone? Is my flesh bronze?
18Jb 6:13 Do I have any power to help myself, now that success has been driven from me?
18Jb 6:14 "A despairing man should have the devotion of his friends, even though he forsakes the fear of the Almighty.
18Jb 6:15 But my brothers are as undependable as intermittent streams, as the streams that overflow
18Jb 6:16 when darkened by thawing ice and swollen with melting snow,
18Jb 6:17 but that cease to flow in the dry season, and in the heat vanish from their channels.
18Jb 6:18 Caravans turn aside from their routes; they go up into the wasteland and perish.
18Jb 6:19 The caravans of Tema look for water, the traveling merchants of Sheba look in hope.
18Jb 6:20 They are distressed, because they had been confident; they arrive there, only to be disappointed.
18Jb 6:21 Now you too have proved to be of no help; you see something dreadful and are afraid.
18Jb 6:22 Have I ever said, 'Give something on my behalf, pay a ransom for me from your wealth,
18Jb 6:23 deliver me from the hand of the enemy, ransom me from the clutches of the ruthless'?
18Jb 6:24 "Teach me, and I will be quiet; show me where I have been wrong.
18Jb 6:25 How painful are honest words! But what do your arguments prove?
18Jb 6:26 Do you mean to correct what I say, and treat the words of a despairing man as wind?
18Jb 6:27 You would even cast lots for the fatherless and barter away your friend.
18Jb 6:28 "But now be so kind as to look at me. Would I lie to your face?
18Jb 6:29 Relent, do not be unjust; reconsider, for my integrity is at stake.
18Jb 6:30 Is there any wickedness on my lips? Can my mouth not discern malice?
18Jb 7:1 "Does not man have hard service on earth? Are not his days like those of a hired man?
18Jb 7:2 Like a slave longing for the evening shadows, or a hired man waiting eagerly for his wages,
18Jb 7:3 so I have been allotted months of futility, and nights of misery have been assigned to me.
18Jb 7:4 When I lie down I think, 'How long before I get up?' The night drags on, and I toss till dawn.
18Jb 7:5 My body is clothed with worms and scabs, my skin is broken and festering.
18Jb 7:6 "My days are swifter than a weaver's shuttle, and they come to an end without hope.
18Jb 7:7 Remember, O God, that my life is but a breath; my eyes will never see happiness again.
18Jb 7:8 The eye that now sees me will see me no longer; you will look for me, but I will be no more.
18Jb 7:9 As a cloud vanishes and is gone, so he who goes down to the grave does not return.
18Jb 7:10 He will never come to his house again; his place will know him no more.
18Jb 7:11 "Therefore I will not keep silent; I will speak out in the anguish of my spirit, I will complain in the bitterness of my soul.
18Jb 7:12 Am I the sea, or the monster of the deep, that you put me under guard?
18Jb 7:13 When I think my bed will comfort me and my couch will ease my complaint,
18Jb 7:14 even then you frighten me with dreams and terrify me with visions,
18Jb 7:15 so that I prefer strangling and death, rather than this body of mine.
18Jb 7:16 I despise my life; I would not live forever. Let me alone; my days have no meaning.
18Jb 7:17 "What is man that you make so much of him, that you give him so much attention,
18Jb 7:18 that you examine him every morning and test him every moment?
18Jb 7:19 Will you never look away from me, or let me alone even for an instant?
18Jb 7:20 If I have sinned, what have I done to you, O watcher of men? Why have you made me your target? Have I become a burden to you?
18Jb 7:21 Why do you not pardon my offenses and forgive my sins? For I will soon lie down in the dust; you will search for me, but I will be no more."
18Jb 8:1 Then Bildad the Shuhite replied£º
18Jb 8:2 "How long will you say such things? Your words are a blustering wind.
18Jb 8:3 Does God pervert justice? Does the Almighty pervert what is right?
18Jb 8:4 When your children sinned against him, he gave them over to the penalty of their sin.
18Jb 8:5 But if you will look to God and plead with the Almighty,
18Jb 8:6 if you are pure and upright, even now he will rouse himself on your behalf and restore you to your rightful place.
18Jb 8:7 Your beginnings will seem humble, so prosperous will your future be.
18Jb 8:8 "Ask the former generations and find out what their fathers learned,
18Jb 8:9 for we were born only yesterday and know nothing, and our days on earth are but a shadow.
18Jb 8:10 Will they not instruct you and tell you? Will they not bring forth words from their understanding?
18Jb 8:11 Can papyrus grow tall where there is no marsh? Can reeds thrive without water?
18Jb 8:12 While still growing and uncut, they wither more quickly than grass.
18Jb 8:13 Such is the destiny of all who forget God; so perishes the hope of the godless.
18Jb 8:14 What he trusts in is fragile; what he relies on is a spider's web.
18Jb 8:15 He leans on his web, but it gives way; he clings to it, but it does not hold.
18Jb 8:16 He is like a well-watered plant in the sunshine, spreading its shoots over the garden;
18Jb 8:17 it entwines its roots around a pile of rocks and looks for a place among the stones.
18Jb 8:18 But when it is torn from its spot, that place disowns it and says, 'I never saw you.'
18Jb 8:19 Surely its life withers away, and from the soil other plants grow.
18Jb 8:20 "Surely God does not reject a blameless man or strengthen the hands of evildoers.
18Jb 8:21 He will yet fill your mouth with laughter and your lips with shouts of joy.
18Jb 8:22 Your enemies will be clothed in shame, and the tents of the wicked will be no more."
18Jb 9:1 Then Job replied£º
18Jb 9:2 "Indeed, I know that this is true. But how can a mortal be righteous before God?
18Jb 9:3 Though one wished to dispute with him, he could not answer him one time out of a thousand.
18Jb 9:4 His wisdom is profound, his power is vast. Who has resisted him and come out unscathed?
18Jb 9:5 He moves mountains without their knowing it and overturns them in his anger.
18Jb 9:6 He shakes the earth from its place and makes its pillars tremble.
18Jb 9:7 He speaks to the sun and it does not shine; he seals off the light of the stars.
18Jb 9:8 He alone stretches out the heavens and treads on the waves of the sea.
18Jb 9:9 He is the Maker of the Bear and Orion, the Pleiades and the constellations of the south.
18Jb 9:10 He performs wonders that cannot be fathomed, miracles that cannot be counted.
18Jb 9:11 When he passes me, I cannot see him; when he goes by, I cannot perceive him.
18Jb 9:12 If he snatches away, who can stop him? Who can say to him, 'What are you doing?'
18Jb 9:13 God does not restrain his anger; even the cohorts of Rahab cowered at his feet.
18Jb 9:14 "How then can I dispute with him? How can I find words to argue with him?
18Jb 9:15 Though I were innocent, I could not answer him; I could only plead with my Judge for mercy.
18Jb 9:16 Even if I summoned him and he responded, I do not believe he would give me a hearing.
18Jb 9:17 He would crush me with a storm and multiply my wounds for no reason.
18Jb 9:18 He would not let me regain my breath but would overwhelm me with misery.
18Jb 9:19 If it is a matter of strength, he is mighty! And if it is a matter of justice, who will summon him?
18Jb 9:20 Even if I were innocent, my mouth would condemn me; if I were blameless, it would pronounce me guilty.
18Jb 9:21 "Although I am blameless, I have no concern for myself; I despise my own life.
18Jb 9:22 It is all the same; that is why I say, 'He destroys both the blameless and the wicked.'
18Jb 9:23 When a scourge brings sudden death, he mocks the despair of the innocent.
18Jb 9:24 When a land falls into the hands of the wicked, he blindfolds its judges. If it is not he, then who is it?
18Jb 9:25 "My days are swifter than a runner; they fly away without a glimpse of joy.
18Jb 9:26 They skim past like boats of papyrus, like eagles swooping down on their prey.
18Jb 9:27 If I say, 'I will forget my complaint, I will change my expression, and smile,'
18Jb 9:28 I still dread all my sufferings, for I know you will not hold me innocent.
18Jb 9:29 Since I am already found guilty, why should I struggle in vain?
18Jb 9:30 Even if I washed myself with soap and my hands with washing soda,
18Jb 9:31 you would plunge me into a slime pit so that even my clothes would detest me.
18Jb 9:32 "He is not a man like me that I might answer him, that we might confront each other in court.
18Jb 9:33 If only there were someone to arbitrate between us, to lay his hand upon us both,
18Jb 9:34 someone to remove God's rod from me, so that his terror would frighten me no more.
18Jb 9:35 Then I would speak up without fear of him, but as it now stands with me, I cannot.
18Jb 10:1 "I loathe my very life; therefore I will give free rein to my complaint and speak out in the bitterness of my soul.
18Jb 10:2 I will say to God£º Do not condemn me, but tell me what charges you have against me.
18Jb 10:3 Does it please you to oppress me, to spurn the work of your hands, while you smile on the schemes of the wicked?
18Jb 10:4 Do you have eyes of flesh? Do you see as a mortal sees?
18Jb 10:5 Are your days like those of a mortal or your years like those of a man,
18Jb 10:6 that you must search out my faults and probe after my sin--
18Jb 10:7 though you know that I am not guilty and that no one can rescue me from your hand?
18Jb 10:8 "Your hands shaped me and made me. Will you now turn and destroy me?
18Jb 10:9 Remember that you molded me like clay. Will you now turn me to dust again?
18Jb 10:10 Did you not pour me out like milk and curdle me like cheese,
18Jb 10:11 clothe me with skin and flesh and knit me together with bones and sinews?
18Jb 10:12 You gave me life and showed me kindness, and in your providence watched over my spirit.
18Jb 10:13 "But this is what you concealed in your heart, and I know that this was in your mind£º
18Jb 10:14 If I sinned, you would be watching me and would not let my offense go unpunished.
18Jb 10:15 If I am guilty--woe to me! Even if I am innocent, I cannot lift my head, for I am full of shame and drowned in my affliction.
18Jb 10:16 If I hold my head high, you stalk me like a lion and again display your awesome power against me.
18Jb 10:17 You bring new witnesses against me and increase your anger toward me; your forces come against me wave upon wave.
18Jb 10:18 "Why then did you bring me out of the womb? I wish I had died before any eye saw me.
18Jb 10:19 If only I had never come into being, or had been carried straight from the womb to the grave!
18Jb 10:20 Are not my few days almost over? Turn away from me so I can have a moment's joy
18Jb 10:21 before I go to the place of no return, to the land of gloom and deep shadow,
18Jb 10:22 to the land of deepest night, of deep shadow and disorder, where even the light is like darkness."
18Jb 11:1 Then Zophar the Naamathite replied£º
18Jb 11:2 "Are all these words to go unanswered? Is this talker to be vindicated?
18Jb 11:3 Will your idle talk reduce men to silence? Will no one rebuke you when you mock?
18Jb 11:4 You say to God, 'My beliefs are flawless and I am pure in your sight.'
18Jb 11:5 Oh, how I wish that God would speak, that he would open his lips against you
18Jb 11:6 and disclose to you the secrets of wisdom, for true wisdom has two sides. Know this£º God has even forgotten some of your sin.
18Jb 11:7 "Can you fathom the mysteries of God? Can you probe the limits of the Almighty?
18Jb 11:8 They are higher than the heavens--what can you do? They are deeper than the depths of the grave--what can you know?
18Jb 11:9 Their measure is longer than the earth and wider than the sea.
18Jb 11:10 "If he comes along and confines you in prison and convenes a court, who can oppose him?
18Jb 11:11 Surely he recognizes deceitful men; and when he sees evil, does he not take note?
18Jb 11:12 But a witless man can no more become wise than a wild donkey's colt can be born a man.
18Jb 11:13 "Yet if you devote your heart to him and stretch out your hands to him,
18Jb 11:14 if you put away the sin that is in your hand and allow no evil to dwell in your tent,
18Jb 11:15 then you will lift up your face without shame; you will stand firm and without fear.
18Jb 11:16 You will surely forget your trouble, recalling it only as waters gone by.
18Jb 11:17 Life will be brighter than noonday, and darkness will become like morning.
18Jb 11:18 You will be secure, because there is hope; you will look about you and take your rest in safety.
18Jb 11:19 You will lie down, with no one to make you afraid, and many will court your favor.
18Jb 11:20 But the eyes of the wicked will fail, and escape will elude them; their hope will become a dying gasp."
18Jb 12:1 Then Job replied£º
18Jb 12:2 "Doubtless you are the people, and wisdom will die with you!
18Jb 12:3 But I have a mind as well as you; I am not inferior to you. Who does not know all these things?
18Jb 12:4 "I have become a laughingstock to my friends, though I called upon God and he answered--a mere laughingstock, though righteous and blameless!
18Jb 12:5 Men at ease have contempt for misfortune as the fate of those whose feet are slipping.
18Jb 12:6 The tents of marauders are undisturbed, and those who provoke God are secure--those who carry their god in their hands.
18Jb 12:7 "But ask the animals, and they will teach you, or the birds of the air, and they will tell you;
18Jb 12:8 or speak to the earth, and it will teach you, or let the fish of the sea inform you.
18Jb 12:9 Which of all these does not know that the hand of the LORD has done this?
18Jb 12:10 In his hand is the life of every creature and the breath of all mankind.
18Jb 12:11 Does not the ear test words as the tongue tastes food?
18Jb 12:12 Is not wisdom found among the aged? Does not long life bring understanding?
18Jb 12:13 "To God belong wisdom and power; counsel and understanding are his.
18Jb 12:14 What he tears down cannot be rebuilt; the man he imprisons cannot be released.
18Jb 12:15 If he holds back the waters, there is drought; if he lets them loose, they devastate the land.
18Jb 12:16 To him belong strength and victory; both deceived and deceiver are his.
18Jb 12:17 He leads counselors away stripped and makes fools of judges.
18Jb 12:18 He takes off the shackles put on by kings and ties a loincloth around their waist.
18Jb 12:19 He leads priests away stripped and overthrows men long established.
18Jb 12:20 He silences the lips of trusted advisers and takes away the discernment of elders.
18Jb 12:21 He pours contempt on nobles and disarms the mighty.
18Jb 12:22 He reveals the deep things of darkness and brings deep shadows into the light.
18Jb 12:23 He makes nations great, and destroys them; he enlarges nations, and disperses them.
18Jb 12:24 He deprives the leaders of the earth of their reason; he sends them wandering through a trackless waste.
18Jb 12:25 They grope in darkness with no light; he makes them stagger like drunkards.
18Jb 13:1 "My eyes have seen all this, my ears have heard and understood it.
18Jb 13:2 What you know, I also know; I am not inferior to you.
18Jb 13:3 But I desire to speak to the Almighty and to argue my case with God.
18Jb 13:4 You, however, smear me with lies; you are worthless physicians, all of you!
18Jb 13:5 If only you would be altogether silent! For you, that would be wisdom.
18Jb 13:6 Hear now my argument; listen to the plea of my lips.
18Jb 13:7 Will you speak wickedly on God's behalf? Will you speak deceitfully for him?
18Jb 13:8 Will you show him partiality? Will you argue the case for God?
18Jb 13:9 Would it turn out well if he examined you? Could you deceive him as you might deceive men?
18Jb 13:10 He would surely rebuke you if you secretly showed partiality.
18Jb 13:11 Would not his splendor terrify you? Would not the dread of him fall on you?
18Jb 13:12 Your maxims are proverbs of ashes; your defenses are defenses of clay.
18Jb 13:13 "Keep silent and let me speak; then let come to me what may.
18Jb 13:14 Why do I put myself in jeopardy and take my life in my hands?
18Jb 13:15 Though he slay me, yet will I hope in him; I will surely defend my ways to his face.
18Jb 13:16 Indeed, this will turn out for my deliverance, for no godless man would dare come before him!
18Jb 13:17 Listen carefully to my words; let your ears take in what I say.
18Jb 13:18 Now that I have prepared my case, I know I will be vindicated.
18Jb 13:19 Can anyone bring charges against me? If so, I will be silent and die.
18Jb 13:20 "Only grant me these two things, O God, and then I will not hide from you£º
18Jb 13:21 Withdraw your hand far from me, and stop frightening me with your terrors.
18Jb 13:22 Then summon me and I will answer, or let me speak, and you reply.
18Jb 13:23 How many wrongs and sins have I committed? Show me my offense and my sin.
18Jb 13:24 Why do you hide your face and consider me your enemy?
18Jb 13:25 Will you torment a windblown leaf? Will you chase after dry chaff?
18Jb 13:26 For you write down bitter things against me and make me inherit the sins of my youth.
18Jb 13:27 You fasten my feet in shackles; you keep close watch on all my paths by putting marks on the soles of my feet.
18Jb 13:28 "So man wastes away like something rotten, like a garment eaten by moths.
18Jb 14:1 "Man born of woman is of few days and full of trouble.
18Jb 14:2 He springs up like a flower and withers away; like a fleeting shadow, he does not endure.
18Jb 14:3 Do you fix your eye on such a one? Will you bring him before you for judgment?
18Jb 14:4 Who can bring what is pure from the impure? No one!
18Jb 14:5 Man's days are determined; you have decreed the number of his months and have set limits he cannot exceed.
18Jb 14:6 So look away from him and let him alone, till he has put in his time like a hired man.
18Jb 14:7 "At least there is hope for a tree£º If it is cut down, it will sprout again, and its new shoots will not fail.
18Jb 14:8 Its roots may grow old in the ground and its stump die in the soil,
18Jb 14:9 yet at the scent of water it will bud and put forth shoots like a plant.
18Jb 14:10 But man dies and is laid low; he breathes his last and is no more.
18Jb 14:11 As water disappears from the sea or a riverbed becomes parched and dry,
18Jb 14:12 so man lies down and does not rise; till the heavens are no more, men will not awake or be roused from their sleep.
18Jb 14:13 "If only you would hide me in the grave and conceal me till your anger has passed! If only you would set me a time and then remember me!
18Jb 14:14 If a man dies, will he live again? All the days of my hard service I will wait for my renewal to come.
18Jb 14:15 You will call and I will answer you; you will long for the creature your hands have made.
18Jb 14:16 Surely then you will count my steps but not keep track of my sin.
18Jb 14:17 My offenses will be sealed up in a bag; you will cover over my sin.
18Jb 14:18 "But as a mountain erodes and crumbles and as a rock is moved from its place,
18Jb 14:19 as water wears away stones and torrents wash away the soil, so you destroy man's hope.
18Jb 14:20 You overpower him once for all, and he is gone; you change his countenance and send him away.
18Jb 14:21 If his sons are honored, he does not know it; if they are brought low, he does not see it.
18Jb 14:22 He feels but the pain of his own body and mourns only for himself."
18Jb 15:1 Then Eliphaz the Temanite replied£º
18Jb 15:2 "Would a wise man answer with empty notions or fill his belly with the hot east wind?
18Jb 15:3 Would he argue with useless words, with speeches that have no value?
18Jb 15:4 But you even undermine piety and hinder devotion to God.
18Jb 15:5 Your sin prompts your mouth; you adopt the tongue of the crafty.
18Jb 15:6 Your own mouth condemns you, not mine; your own lips testify against you.
18Jb 15:7 "Are you the first man ever born? Were you brought forth before the hills?
18Jb 15:8 Do you listen in on God's council? Do you limit wisdom to yourself?
18Jb 15:9 What do you know that we do not know? What insights do you have that we do not have?
18Jb 15:10 The gray-haired and the aged are on our side, men even older than your father.
18Jb 15:11 Are God's consolations not enough for you, words spoken gently to you?
18Jb 15:12 Why has your heart carried you away, and why do your eyes flash,
18Jb 15:13 so that you vent your rage against God and pour out such words from your mouth?
18Jb 15:14 "What is man, that he could be pure, or one born of woman, that he could be righteous?
18Jb 15:15 If God places no trust in his holy ones, if even the heavens are not pure in his eyes,
18Jb 15:16 how much less man, who is vile and corrupt, who drinks up evil like water!
18Jb 15:17 "Listen to me and I will explain to you; let me tell you what I have seen,
18Jb 15:18 what wise men have declared, hiding nothing received from their fathers
18Jb 15:19 (to whom alone the land was given when no alien passed among them)£º
18Jb 15:20 All his days the wicked man suffers torment, the ruthless through all the years stored up for him.
18Jb 15:21 Terrifying sounds fill his ears; when all seems well, marauders attack him.
18Jb 15:22 He despairs of escaping the darkness; he is marked for the sword.
18Jb 15:23 He wanders about--food for vultures; he knows the day of darkness is at hand.
18Jb 15:24 Distress and anguish fill him with terror; they overwhelm him, like a king poised to attack,
18Jb 15:25 because he shakes his fist at God and vaunts himself against the Almighty,
18Jb 15:26 defiantly charging against him with a thick, strong shield.
18Jb 15:27 "Though his face is covered with fat and his waist bulges with flesh,
18Jb 15:28 he will inhabit ruined towns and houses where no one lives, houses crumbling to rubble.
18Jb 15:29 He will no longer be rich and his wealth will not endure, nor will his possessions spread over the land.
18Jb 15:30 He will not escape the darkness; a flame will wither his shoots, and the breath of God's mouth will carry him away.
18Jb 15:31 Let him not deceive himself by trusting what is worthless, for he will get nothing in return.
18Jb 15:32 Before his time he will be paid in full, and his branches will not flourish.
18Jb 15:33 He will be like a vine stripped of its unripe grapes, like an olive tree shedding its blossoms.
18Jb 15:34 For the company of the godless will be barren, and fire will consume the tents of those who love bribes.
18Jb 15:35 They conceive trouble and give birth to evil; their womb fashions deceit."
18Jb 16:1 Then Job replied£º
18Jb 16:2 "I have heard many things like these; miserable comforters are you all!
18Jb 16:3 Will your long-winded speeches never end? What ails you that you keep on arguing?
18Jb 16:4 I also could speak like you, if you were in my place; I could make fine speeches against you and shake my head at you.
18Jb 16:5 But my mouth would encourage you; comfort from my lips would bring you relief.
18Jb 16:6 "Yet if I speak, my pain is not relieved; and if I refrain, it does not go away.
18Jb 16:7 Surely, O God, you have worn me out; you have devastated my entire household.
18Jb 16:8 You have bound me--and it has become a witness; my gauntness rises up and testifies against me.
18Jb 16:9 God assails me and tears me in his anger and gnashes his teeth at me; my opponent fastens on me his piercing eyes.
18Jb 16:10 Men open their mouths to jeer at me; they strike my cheek in scorn and unite together against me.
18Jb 16:11 God has turned me over to evil men and thrown me into the clutches of the wicked.
18Jb 16:12 All was well with me, but he shattered me; he seized me by the neck and crushed me. He has made me his target;
18Jb 16:13 his archers surround me. Without pity, he pierces my kidneys and spills my gall on the ground.
18Jb 16:14 Again and again he bursts upon me; he rushes at me like a warrior.
18Jb 16:15 "I have sewed sackcloth over my skin and buried my brow in the dust.
18Jb 16:16 My face is red with weeping, deep shadows ring my eyes;
18Jb 16:17 yet my hands have been free of violence and my prayer is pure.
18Jb 16:18 "O earth, do not cover my blood; may my cry never be laid to rest!
18Jb 16:19 Even now my witness is in heaven; my advocate is on high.
18Jb 16:20 My intercessor is my friend as my eyes pour out tears to God;
18Jb 16:21 on behalf of a man he pleads with God as a man pleads for his friend.
18Jb 16:22 "Only a few years will pass before I go on the journey of no return.
18Jb 17:1 My spirit is broken, my days are cut short, the grave awaits me.
18Jb 17:2 Surely mockers surround me; my eyes must dwell on their hostility.
18Jb 17:3 "Give me, O God, the pledge you demand. Who else will put up security for me?
18Jb 17:4 You have closed their minds to understanding; therefore you will not let them triumph.
18Jb 17:5 If a man denounces his friends for reward, the eyes of his children will fail.
18Jb 17:6 "God has made me a byword to everyone, a man in whose face people spit.
18Jb 17:7 My eyes have grown dim with grief; my whole frame is but a shadow.
18Jb 17:8 Upright men are appalled at this; the innocent are aroused against the ungodly.
18Jb 17:9 Nevertheless, the righteous will hold to their ways, and those with clean hands will grow stronger.
18Jb 17:10 "But come on, all of you, try again! I will not find a wise man among you.
18Jb 17:11 My days have passed, my plans are shattered, and so are the desires of my heart.
18Jb 17:12 These men turn night into day; in the face of darkness they say, 'Light is near.'
18Jb 17:13 If the only home I hope for is the grave, if I spread out my bed in darkness,
18Jb 17:14 if I say to corruption, 'You are my father,' and to the worm, 'My mother' or 'My sister,'
18Jb 17:15 where then is my hope? Who can see any hope for me?
18Jb 17:16 Will it go down to the gates of death? Will we descend together into the dust?"
18Jb 18:1 Then Bildad the Shuhite replied£º
18Jb 18:2 "When will you end these speeches? Be sensible, and then we can talk.
18Jb 18:3 Why are we regarded as cattle and considered stupid in your sight?
18Jb 18:4 You who tear yourself to pieces in your anger, is the earth to be abandoned for your sake? Or must the rocks be moved from their place?
18Jb 18:5 "The lamp of the wicked is snuffed out; the flame of his fire stops burning.
18Jb 18:6 The light in his tent becomes dark; the lamp beside him goes out.
18Jb 18:7 The vigor of his step is weakened; his own schemes throw him down.
18Jb 18:8 His feet thrust him into a net and he wanders into its mesh.
18Jb 18:9 A trap seizes him by the heel; a snare holds him fast.
18Jb 18:10 A noose is hidden for him on the ground; a trap lies in his path.
18Jb 18:11 Terrors startle him on every side and dog his every step.
18Jb 18:12 Calamity is hungry for him; disaster is ready for him when he falls.
18Jb 18:13 It eats away parts of his skin; death's firstborn devours his limbs.
18Jb 18:14 He is torn from the security of his tent and marched off to the king of terrors.
18Jb 18:15 Fire resides in his tent; burning sulfur is scattered over his dwelling.
18Jb 18:16 His roots dry up below and his branches wither above.
18Jb 18:17 The memory of him perishes from the earth; he has no name in the land.
18Jb 18:18 He is driven from light into darkness and is banished from the world.
18Jb 18:19 He has no offspring or descendants among his people, no survivor where once he lived.
18Jb 18:20 Men of the west are appalled at his fate; men of the east are seized with horror.
18Jb 18:21 Surely such is the dwelling of an evil man; such is the place of one who knows not God."
18Jb 19:1 Then Job replied£º
18Jb 19:2 "How long will you torment me and crush me with words?
18Jb 19:3 Ten times now you have reproached me; shamelessly you attack me.
18Jb 19:4 If it is true that I have gone astray, my error remains my concern alone.
18Jb 19:5 If indeed you would exalt yourselves above me and use my humiliation against me,
18Jb 19:6 then know that God has wronged me and drawn his net around me.
18Jb 19:7 "Though I cry, 'I've been wronged!' I get no response; though I call for help, there is no justice.
18Jb 19:8 He has blocked my way so I cannot pass; he has shrouded my paths in darkness.
18Jb 19:9 He has stripped me of my honor and removed the crown from my head.
18Jb 19:10 He tears me down on every side till I am gone; he uproots my hope like a tree.
18Jb 19:11 His anger burns against me; he counts me among his enemies.
18Jb 19:12 His troops advance in force; they build a siege ramp against me and encamp around my tent.
18Jb 19:13 "He has alienated my brothers from me; my acquaintances are completely estranged from me.
18Jb 19:14 My kinsmen have gone away; my friends have forgotten me.
18Jb 19:15 My guests and my maidservants count me a stranger; they look upon me as an alien.
18Jb 19:16 I summon my servant, but he does not answer, though I beg him with my own mouth.
18Jb 19:17 My breath is offensive to my wife; I am loathsome to my own brothers.
18Jb 19:18 Even the little boys scorn me; when I appear, they ridicule me.
18Jb 19:19 All my intimate friends detest me; those I love have turned against me.
18Jb 19:20 I am nothing but skin and bones; I have escaped with only the skin of my teeth.
18Jb 19:21 "Have pity on me, my friends, have pity, for the hand of God has struck me.
18Jb 19:22 Why do you pursue me as God does? Will you never get enough of my flesh?
18Jb 19:23 "Oh, that my words were recorded, that they were written on a scroll,
18Jb 19:24 that they were inscribed with an iron tool on lead, or engraved in rock forever!
18Jb 19:25 I know that my Redeemer lives, and that in the end he will stand upon the earth.
18Jb 19:26 And after my skin has been destroyed, yet in my flesh I will see God;
18Jb 19:27 I myself will see him with my own eyes--I, and not another. How my heart yearns within me!
18Jb 19:28 "If you say, 'How we will hound him, since the root of the trouble lies in him,'
18Jb 19:29 you should fear the sword yourselves; for wrath will bring punishment by the sword, and then you will know that there is judgment."
18Jb 20:1 Then Zophar the Naamathite replied£º
18Jb 20:2 "My troubled thoughts prompt me to answer because I am greatly disturbed.
18Jb 20:3 I hear a rebuke that dishonors me, and my understanding inspires me to reply.
18Jb 20:4 "Surely you know how it has been from of old, ever since man was placed on the earth,
18Jb 20:5 that the mirth of the wicked is brief, the joy of the godless lasts but a moment.
18Jb 20:6 Though his pride reaches to the heavens and his head touches the clouds,
18Jb 20:7 he will perish forever, like his own dung; those who have seen him will say, 'Where is he?'
18Jb 20:8 Like a dream he flies away, no more to be found, banished like a vision of the night.
18Jb 20:9 The eye that saw him will not see him again; his place will look on him no more.
18Jb 20:10 His children must make amends to the poor; his own hands must give back his wealth.
18Jb 20:11 The youthful vigor that fills his bones will lie with him in the dust.
18Jb 20:12 "Though evil is sweet in his mouth and he hides it under his tongue,
18Jb 20:13 though he cannot bear to let it go and keeps it in his mouth,
18Jb 20:14 yet his food will turn sour in his stomach; it will become the venom of serpents within him.
18Jb 20:15 He will spit out the riches he swallowed; God will make his stomach vomit them up.
18Jb 20:16 He will suck the poison of serpents; the fangs of an adder will kill him.
18Jb 20:17 He will not enjoy the streams, the rivers flowing with honey and cream.
18Jb 20:18 What he toiled for he must give back uneaten; he will not enjoy the profit from his trading.
18Jb 20:19 For he has oppressed the poor and left them destitute; he has seized houses he did not build.
18Jb 20:20 "Surely he will have no respite from his craving; he cannot save himself by his treasure.
18Jb 20:21 Nothing is left for him to devour; his prosperity will not endure.
18Jb 20:22 In the midst of his plenty, distress will overtake him; the full force of misery will come upon him.
18Jb 20:23 When he has filled his belly, God will vent his burning anger against him and rain down his blows upon him.
18Jb 20:24 Though he flees from an iron weapon, a bronze-tipped arrow pierces him.
18Jb 20:25 He pulls it out of his back, the gleaming point out of his liver. Terrors will come over him;
18Jb 20:26 total darkness lies in wait for his treasures. A fire unfanned will consume him and devour what is left in his tent.
18Jb 20:27 The heavens will expose his guilt; the earth will rise up against him.
18Jb 20:28 A flood will carry off his house, rushing waters on the day of God's wrath.
18Jb 20:29 Such is the fate God allots the wicked, the heritage appointed for them by God."
18Jb 21:1 Then Job replied£º
18Jb 21:2 "Listen carefully to my words; let this be the consolation you give me.
18Jb 21:3 Bear with me while I speak, and after I have spoken, mock on.
18Jb 21:4 "Is my complaint directed to man? Why should I not be impatient?
18Jb 21:5 Look at me and be astonished; clap your hand over your mouth.
18Jb 21:6 When I think about this, I am terrified; trembling seizes my body.
18Jb 21:7 Why do the wicked live on, growing old and increasing in power?
18Jb 21:8 They see their children established around them, their offspring before their eyes.
18Jb 21:9 Their homes are safe and free from fear; the rod of God is not upon them.
18Jb 21:10 Their bulls never fail to breed; their cows calve and do not miscarry.
18Jb 21:11 They send forth their children as a flock; their little ones dance about.
18Jb 21:12 They sing to the music of tambourine and harp; they make merry to the sound of the flute.
18Jb 21:13 They spend their years in prosperity and go down to the grave in peace.
18Jb 21:14 Yet they say to God, 'Leave us alone! We have no desire to know your ways.
18Jb 21:15 Who is the Almighty, that we should serve him? What would we gain by praying to him?'
18Jb 21:16 But their prosperity is not in their own hands, so I stand aloof from the counsel of the wicked.
18Jb 21:17 "Yet how often is the lamp of the wicked snuffed out? How often does calamity come upon them, the fate God allots in his anger?
18Jb 21:18 How often are they like straw before the wind, like chaff swept away by a gale?
18Jb 21:19 It is said,'God stores up a man's punishment for his sons.' Let him repay the man himself, so that he will know it!
18Jb 21:20 Let his own eyes see his destruction; let him drink of the wrath of the Almighty.
18Jb 21:21 For what does he care about the family he leaves behind when his allotted months come to an end?
18Jb 21:22 "Can anyone teach knowledge to God, since he judges even the highest?
18Jb 21:23 One man dies in full vigor, completely secure and at ease,
18Jb 21:24 his body well nourished, his bones rich with marrow.
18Jb 21:25 Another man dies in bitterness of soul, never having enjoyed anything good.
18Jb 21:26 Side by side they lie in the dust, and worms cover them both.
18Jb 21:27 "I know full well what you are thinking, the schemes by which you would wrong me.
18Jb 21:28 You say, 'Where now is the great man's house, the tents where wicked men lived?'
18Jb 21:29 Have you never questioned those who travel? Have you paid no regard to their accounts--
18Jb 21:30 that the evil man is spared from the day of calamity, that he is delivered from the day of wrath?
18Jb 21:31 Who denounces his conduct to his face? Who repays him for what he has done?
18Jb 21:32 He is carried to the grave, and watch is kept over his tomb.
18Jb 21:33 The soil in the valley is sweet to him; all men follow after him, and a countless throng goes before him.
18Jb 21:34 "So how can you console me with your nonsense? Nothing is left of your answers but falsehood!"
18Jb 22:1 Then Eliphaz the Temanite replied£º
18Jb 22:2 "Can a man be of benefit to God? Can even a wise man benefit him?
18Jb 22:3 What pleasure would it give the Almighty if you were righteous? What would he gain if your ways were blameless?
18Jb 22:4 "Is it for your piety that he rebukes you and brings charges against you?
18Jb 22:5 Is not your wickedness great? Are not your sins endless?
18Jb 22:6 You demanded security from your brothers for no reason; you stripped men of their clothing, leaving them naked.
18Jb 22:7 You gave no water to the weary and you withheld food from the hungry,
18Jb 22:8 though you were a powerful man, owning land--an honored man, living on it.
18Jb 22:9 And you sent widows away empty-handed and broke the strength of the fatherless.
18Jb 22:10 That is why snares are all around you, why sudden peril terrifies you,
18Jb 22:11 why it is so dark you cannot see, and why a flood of water covers you.
18Jb 22:12 "Is not God in the heights of heaven? And see how lofty are the highest stars!
18Jb 22:13 Yet you say, 'What does God know? Does he judge through such darkness?
18Jb 22:14 Thick clouds veil him, so he does not see us as he goes about in the vaulted heavens.'
18Jb 22:15 Will you keep to the old path that evil men have trod?
18Jb 22:16 They were carried off before their time, their foundations washed away by a flood.
18Jb 22:17 They said to God, 'Leave us alone! What can the Almighty do to us?'
18Jb 22:18 Yet it was he who filled their houses with good things, so I stand aloof from the counsel of the wicked.
18Jb 22:19 "The righteous see their ruin and rejoice; the innocent mock them, saying,
18Jb 22:20 'Surely our foes are destroyed, and fire devours their wealth.'
18Jb 22:21 "Submit to God and be at peace with him; in this way prosperity will come to you.
18Jb 22:22 Accept instruction from his mouth and lay up his words in your heart.
18Jb 22:23 If you return to the Almighty, you will be restored£º If you remove wickedness far from your tent
18Jb 22:24 and assign your nuggets to the dust, your gold of Ophir to the rocks in the ravines,
18Jb 22:25 then the Almighty will be your gold, the choicest silver for you.
18Jb 22:26 Surely then you will find delight in the Almighty and will lift up your face to God.
18Jb 22:27 You will pray to him, and he will hear you, and you will fulfill your vows.
18Jb 22:28 What you decide on will be done, and light will shine on your ways.
18Jb 22:29 When men are brought low and you say, 'Lift them up!' then he will save the downcast.
18Jb 22:30 He will deliver even one who is not innocent, who will be delivered through the cleanness of your hands."
18Jb 23:1 Then Job replied£º
18Jb 23:2 "Even today my complaint is bitter; his hand is heavy in spite of my groaning.
18Jb 23:3 If only I knew where to find him; if only I could go to his dwelling!
18Jb 23:4 I would state my case before him and fill my mouth with arguments.
18Jb 23:5 I would find out what he would answer me, and consider what he would say.
18Jb 23:6 Would he oppose me with great power? No, he would not press charges against me.
18Jb 23:7 There an upright man could present his case before him, and I would be delivered forever from my judge.
18Jb 23:8 "But if I go to the east, he is not there; if I go to the west, I do not find him.
18Jb 23:9 When he is at work in the north, I do not see him; when he turns to the south, I catch no glimpse of him.
18Jb 23:10 But he knows the way that I take; when he has tested me, I will come forth as gold.
18Jb 23:11 My feet have closely followed his steps; I have kept to his way without turning aside.
18Jb 23:12 I have not departed from the commands of his lips; I have treasured the words of his mouth more than my daily bread.
18Jb 23:13 "But he stands alone, and who can oppose him? He does whatever he pleases.
18Jb 23:14 He carries out his decree against me, and many such plans he still has in store.
18Jb 23:15 That is why I am terrified before him; when I think of all this, I fear him.
18Jb 23:16 God has made my heart faint; the Almighty has terrified me.
18Jb 23:17 Yet I am not silenced by the darkness, by the thick darkness that covers my face.
18Jb 24:1 "Why does the Almighty not set times for judgment? Why must those who know him look in vain for such days?
18Jb 24:2 Men move boundary stones; they pasture flocks they have stolen.
18Jb 24:3 They drive away the orphan's donkey and take the widow's ox in pledge.
18Jb 24:4 They thrust the needy from the path and force all the poor of the land into hiding.
18Jb 24:5 Like wild donkeys in the desert, the poor go about their labor of foraging food; the wasteland provides food for their children.
18Jb 24:6 They gather fodder in the fields and glean in the vineyards of the wicked.
18Jb 24:7 Lacking clothes, they spend the night naked; they have nothing to cover themselves in the cold.
18Jb 24:8 They are drenched by mountain rains and hug the rocks for lack of shelter.
18Jb 24:9 The fatherless child is snatched from the breast; the infant of the poor is seized for a debt.
18Jb 24:10 Lacking clothes, they go about naked; they carry the sheaves, but still go hungry.
18Jb 24:11 They crush olives among the terraces; they tread the winepresses, yet suffer thirst.
18Jb 24:12 The groans of the dying rise from the city, and the souls of the wounded cry out for help. But God charges no one with wrongdoing.
18Jb 24:13 "There are those who rebel against the light, who do not know its ways or stay in its paths.
18Jb 24:14 When daylight is gone, the murderer rises up and kills the poor and needy; in the night he steals forth like a thief.
18Jb 24:15 The eye of the adulterer watches for dusk; he thinks, 'No eye will see me,' and he keeps his face concealed.
18Jb 24:16 In the dark, men break into houses, but by day they shut themselves in; they want nothing to do with the light.
18Jb 24:17 For all of them, deep darkness is their morning; they make friends with the terrors of darkness.
18Jb 24:18 "Yet they are foam on the surface of the water; their portion of the land is cursed, so that no one goes to the vineyards.
18Jb 24:19 As heat and drought snatch away the melted snow, so the grave snatches away those who have sinned.
18Jb 24:20 The womb forgets them, the worm feasts on them; evil men are no longer remembered but are broken like a tree.
18Jb 24:21 They prey on the barren and childless woman, and to the widow show no kindness.
18Jb 24:22 But God drags away the mighty by his power; though they become established, they have no assurance of life.
18Jb 24:23 He may let them rest in a feeling of security, but his eyes are on their ways.
18Jb 24:24 For a little while they are exalted, and then they are gone; they are brought low and gathered up like all others; they are cut off like heads of grain.
18Jb 24:25 "If this is not so, who can prove me false and reduce my words to nothing?"
18Jb 25:1 Then Bildad the Shuhite replied£º
18Jb 25:2 "Dominion and awe belong to God; he establishes order in the heights of heaven.
18Jb 25:3 Can his forces be numbered? Upon whom does his light not rise?
18Jb 25:4 How then can a man be righteous before God? How can one born of woman be pure?
18Jb 25:5 If even the moon is not bright and the stars are not pure in his eyes,
18Jb 25:6 how much less man, who is but a maggot--a son of man, who is only a worm!"
18Jb 26:1 Then Job replied£º
18Jb 26:2 "How you have helped the powerless! How you have saved the arm that is feeble!
18Jb 26:3 What advice you have offered to one without wisdom! And what great insight you have displayed!
18Jb 26:4 Who has helped you utter these words? And whose spirit spoke from your mouth?
18Jb 26:5 "The dead are in deep anguish, those beneath the waters and all that live in them.
18Jb 26:6 Death is naked before God; Destruction lies uncovered.
18Jb 26:7 He spreads out the northern skies over empty space; he suspends the earth over nothing.
18Jb 26:8 He wraps up the waters in his clouds, yet the clouds do not burst under their weight.
18Jb 26:9 He covers the face of the full moon, spreading his clouds over it.
18Jb 26:10 He marks out the horizon on the face of the waters for a boundary between light and darkness.
18Jb 26:11 The pillars of the heavens quake, aghast at his rebuke.
18Jb 26:12 By his power he churned up the sea; by his wisdom he cut Rahab to pieces.
18Jb 26:13 By his breath the skies became fair; his hand pierced the gliding serpent.
18Jb 26:14 And these are but the outer fringe of his works; how faint the whisper we hear of him! Who then can understand the thunder of his power?"
18Jb 27:1 And Job continued his discourse£º
18Jb 27:2 "As surely as God lives, who has denied me justice, the Almighty, who has made me taste bitterness of soul,
18Jb 27:3 as long as I have life within me, the breath of God in my nostrils,
18Jb 27:4 my lips will not speak wickedness, and my tongue will utter no deceit.
18Jb 27:5 I will never admit you are in the right; till I die, I will not deny my integrity.
18Jb 27:6 I will maintain my righteousness and never let go of it; my conscience will not reproach me as long as I live.
18Jb 27:7 "May my enemies be like the wicked, my adversaries like the unjust!
18Jb 27:8 For what hope has the godless when he is cut off, when God takes away his life?
18Jb 27:9 Does God listen to his cry when distress comes upon him?
18Jb 27:10 Will he find delight in the Almighty? Will he call upon God at all times?
18Jb 27:11 "I will teach you about the power of God; the ways of the Almighty I will not conceal.
18Jb 27:12 You have all seen this yourselves. Why then this meaningless talk?
18Jb 27:13 "Here is the fate God allots to the wicked, the heritage a ruthless man receives from the Almighty£º
18Jb 27:14 However many his children, their fate is the sword; his offspring will never have enough to eat.
18Jb 27:15 The plague will bury those who survive him, and their widows will not weep for them.
18Jb 27:16 Though he heaps up silver like dust and clothes like piles of clay,
18Jb 27:17 what he lays up the righteous will wear, and the innocent will divide his silver.
18Jb 27:18 The house he builds is like a moth's cocoon, like a hut made by a watchman.
18Jb 27:19 He lies down wealthy, but will do so no more; when he opens his eyes, all is gone.
18Jb 27:20 Terrors overtake him like a flood; a tempest snatches him away in the night.
18Jb 27:21 The east wind carries him off, and he is gone; it sweeps him out of his place.
18Jb 27:22 It hurls itself against him without mercy as he flees headlong from its power.
18Jb 27:23 It claps its hands in derision and hisses him out of his place.
18Jb 28:1 "There is a mine for silver and a place where gold is refined.
18Jb 28:2 Iron is taken from the earth, and copper is smelted from ore.
18Jb 28:3 Man puts an end to the darkness; he searches the farthest recesses for ore in the blackest darkness.
18Jb 28:4 Far from where people dwell he cuts a shaft, in places forgotten by the foot of man; far from men he dangles and sways.
18Jb 28:5 The earth, from which food comes, is transformed below as by fire;
18Jb 28:6 sapphires come from its rocks, and its dust contains nuggets of gold.
18Jb 28:7 No bird of prey knows that hidden path, no falcon's eye has seen it.
18Jb 28:8 Proud beasts do not set foot on it, and no lion prowls there.
18Jb 28:9 Man's hand assaults the flinty rock and lays bare the roots of the mountains.
18Jb 28:10 He tunnels through the rock; his eyes see all its treasures.
18Jb 28:11 He searches the sources of the rivers and brings hidden things to light.
18Jb 28:12 "But where can wisdom be found? Where does understanding dwell?
18Jb 28:13 Man does not comprehend its worth; it cannot be found in the land of the living.
18Jb 28:14 The deep says, 'It is not in me'; the sea says, 'It is not with me.'
18Jb 28:15 It cannot be bought with the finest gold, nor can its price be weighed in silver.
18Jb 28:16 It cannot be bought with the gold of Ophir, with precious onyx or sapphires.
18Jb 28:17 Neither gold nor crystal can compare with it, nor can it be had for jewels of gold.
18Jb 28:18 Coral and jasper are not worthy of mention; the price of wisdom is beyond rubies.
18Jb 28:19 The topaz of Cush cannot compare with it; it cannot be bought with pure gold.
18Jb 28:20 "Where then does wisdom come from? Where does understanding dwell?
18Jb 28:21 It is hidden from the eyes of every living thing, concealed even from the birds of the air.
18Jb 28:22 Destruction and Death say, 'Only a rumor of it has reached our ears.'
18Jb 28:23 God understands the way to it and he alone knows where it dwells,
18Jb 28:24 for he views the ends of the earth and sees everything under the heavens.
18Jb 28:25 When he established the force of the wind and measured out the waters,
18Jb 28:26 when he made a decree for the rain and a path for the thunderstorm,
18Jb 28:27 then he looked at wisdom and appraised it; he confirmed it and tested it.
18Jb 28:28 And he said to man, 'The fear of the Lord--that is wisdom, and to shun evil is understanding.'"
18Jb 29:1 Job continued his discourse£º
18Jb 29:2 "How I long for the months gone by, for the days when God watched over me,
18Jb 29:3 when his lamp shone upon my head and by his light I walked through darkness!
18Jb 29:4 Oh, for the days when I was in my prime, when God's intimate friendship blessed my house,
18Jb 29:5 when the Almighty was still with me and my children were around me,
18Jb 29:6 when my path was drenched with cream and the rock poured out for me streams of olive oil.
18Jb 29:7 "When I went to the gate of the city and took my seat in the public square,
18Jb 29:8 the young men saw me and stepped aside and the old men rose to their feet;
18Jb 29:9 the chief men refrained from speaking and covered their mouths with their hands;
18Jb 29:10 the voices of the nobles were hushed, and their tongues stuck to the roof of their mouths.
18Jb 29:11 Whoever heard me spoke well of me, and those who saw me commended me,
18Jb 29:12 because I rescued the poor who cried for help, and the fatherless who had none to assist him.
18Jb 29:13 The man who was dying blessed me; I made the widow's heart sing.
18Jb 29:14 I put on righteousness as my clothing; justice was my robe and my turban.
18Jb 29:15 I was eyes to the blind and feet to the lame.
18Jb 29:16 I was a father to the needy; I took up the case of the stranger.
18Jb 29:17 I broke the fangs of the wicked and snatched the victims from their teeth.
18Jb 29:18 "I thought, 'I will die in my own house, my days as numerous as the grains of sand.
18Jb 29:19 My roots will reach to the water, and the dew will lie all night on my branches.
18Jb 29:20 My glory will remain fresh in me, the bow ever new in my hand.'
18Jb 29:21 "Men listened to me expectantly, waiting in silence for my counsel.
18Jb 29:22 After I had spoken, they spoke no more; my words fell gently on their ears.
18Jb 29:23 They waited for me as for showers and drank in my words as the spring rain.
18Jb 29:24 When I smiled at them, they scarcely believed it; the light of my face was precious to them.
18Jb 29:25 I chose the way for them and sat as their chief; I dwelt as a king among his troops; I was like one who comforts mourners.
18Jb 30:1 "But now they mock me, men younger than I, whose fathers I would have disdained to put with my sheep dogs.
18Jb 30:2 Of what use was the strength of their hands to me, since their vigor had gone from them?
18Jb 30:3 Haggard from want and hunger, they roamed the parched land in desolate wastelands at night.
18Jb 30:4 In the brush they gathered salt herbs, and their food was the root of the broom tree.
18Jb 30:5 They were banished from their fellow men, shouted at as if they were thieves.
18Jb 30:6 They were forced to live in the dry stream beds, among the rocks and in holes in the ground.
18Jb 30:7 They brayed among the bushes and huddled in the undergrowth.
18Jb 30:8 A base and nameless brood, they were driven out of the land.
18Jb 30:9 "And now their sons mock me in song; I have become a byword among them.
18Jb 30:10 They detest me and keep their distance; they do not hesitate to spit in my face.
18Jb 30:11 Now that God has unstrung my bow and afflicted me, they throw off restraint in my presence.
18Jb 30:12 On my right the tribe attacks; they lay snares for my feet, they build their siege ramps against me.
18Jb 30:13 They break up my road; they succeed in destroying me--without anyone's helping them.
18Jb 30:14 They advance as through a gaping breach; amid the ruins they come rolling in.
18Jb 30:15 Terrors overwhelm me; my dignity is driven away as by the wind, my safety vanishes like a cloud.
18Jb 30:16 "And now my life ebbs away; days of suffering grip me.
18Jb 30:17 Night pierces my bones; my gnawing pains never rest.
18Jb 30:18 In his great power God becomes like clothing to me; he binds me like the neck of my garment.
18Jb 30:19 He throws me into the mud, and I am reduced to dust and ashes.
18Jb 30:20 "I cry out to you, O God, but you do not answer; I stand up, but you merely look at me.
18Jb 30:21 You turn on me ruthlessly; with the might of your hand you attack me.
18Jb 30:22 You snatch me up and drive me before the wind; you toss me about in the storm.
18Jb 30:23 I know you will bring me down to death, to the place appointed for all the living.
18Jb 30:24 "Surely no one lays a hand on a broken man when he cries for help in his distress.
18Jb 30:25 Have I not wept for those in trouble? Has not my soul grieved for the poor?
18Jb 30:26 Yet when I hoped for good, evil came; when I looked for light, then came darkness.
18Jb 30:27 The churning inside me never stops; days of suffering confront me.
18Jb 30:28 I go about blackened, but not by the sun; I stand up in the assembly and cry for help.
18Jb 30:29 I have become a brother of jackals, a companion of owls.
18Jb 30:30 My skin grows black and peels; my body burns with fever.
18Jb 30:31 My harp is tuned to mourning, and my flute to the sound of wailing.
18Jb 31:1 "I made a covenant with my eyes not to look lustfully at a girl.
18Jb 31:2 For what is man's lot from God above, his heritage from the Almighty on high?
18Jb 31:3 Is it not ruin for the wicked, disaster for those who do wrong?
18Jb 31:4 Does he not see my ways and count my every step?
18Jb 31:5 "If I have walked in falsehood or my foot has hurried after deceit--
18Jb 31:6 let God weigh me in honest scales and he will know that I am blameless--
18Jb 31:7 if my steps have turned from the path, if my heart has been led by my eyes, or if my hands have been defiled,
18Jb 31:8 then may others eat what I have sown, and may my crops be uprooted.
18Jb 31:9 "If my heart has been enticed by a woman, or if I have lurked at my neighbor's door,
18Jb 31:10 then may my wife grind another man's grain, and may other men sleep with her.
18Jb 31:11 For that would have been shameful, a sin to be judged.
18Jb 31:12 It is a fire that burns to Destruction; it would have uprooted my harvest.
18Jb 31:13 "If I have denied justice to my menservants and maidservants when they had a grievance against me,
18Jb 31:14 what will I do when God confronts me? What will I answer when called to account?
18Jb 31:15 Did not he who made me in the womb make them? Did not the same one form us both within our mothers?
18Jb 31:16 "If I have denied the desires of the poor or let the eyes of the widow grow weary,
18Jb 31:17 if I have kept my bread to myself, not sharing it with the fatherless--
18Jb 31:18 but from my youth I reared him as would a father, and from my birth I guided the widow--
18Jb 31:19 if I have seen anyone perishing for lack of clothing, or a needy man without a garment,
18Jb 31:20 and his heart did not bless me for warming him with the fleece from my sheep,
18Jb 31:21 if I have raised my hand against the fatherless, knowing that I had influence in court,
18Jb 31:22 then let my arm fall from the shoulder, let it be broken off at the joint.
18Jb 31:23 For I dreaded destruction from God, and for fear of his splendor I could not do such things.
18Jb 31:24 "If I have put my trust in gold or said to pure gold, 'You are my security,'
18Jb 31:25 if I have rejoiced over my great wealth, the fortune my hands had gained,
18Jb 31:26 if I have regarded the sun in its radiance or the moon moving in splendor,
18Jb 31:27 so that my heart was secretly enticed and my hand offered them a kiss of homage,
18Jb 31:28 then these also would be sins to be judged, for I would have been unfaithful to God on high.
18Jb 31:29 "If I have rejoiced at my enemy's misfortune or gloated over the trouble that came to him--
18Jb 31:30 I have not allowed my mouth to sin by invoking a curse against his life--
18Jb 31:31 if the men of my household have never said, 'Who has not had his fill of Job's meat?'--
18Jb 31:32 but no stranger had to spend the night in the street, for my door was always open to the traveler--
18Jb 31:33 if I have concealed my sin as men do, by hiding my guilt in my heart
18Jb 31:34 because I so feared the crowd and so dreaded the contempt of the clans that I kept silent and would not go outside
18Jb 31:35 ("Oh, that I had someone to hear me! I sign now my defense--let the Almighty answer me; let my accuser put his indictment in writing.
18Jb 31:36 Surely I would wear it on my shoulder, I would put it on like a crown.
18Jb 31:37 I would give him an account of my every step; like a prince I would approach him.)--
18Jb 31:38 "if my land cries out against me and all its furrows are wet with tears,
18Jb 31:39 if I have devoured its yield without payment or broken the spirit of its tenants,
18Jb 31:40 then let briers come up instead of wheat and weeds instead of barley." The words of Job are ended.
18Jb 32:1 So these three men stopped answering Job, because he was righteous in his own eyes.
18Jb 32:2 But Elihu son of Barakel the Buzite, of the family of Ram, became very angry with Job for justifying himself rather than God.
18Jb 32:3 He was also angry with the three friends, because they had found no way to refute Job, and yet had condemned him.
18Jb 32:4 Now Elihu had waited before speaking to Job because they were older than he.
18Jb 32:5 But when he saw that the three men had nothing more to say, his anger was aroused.
18Jb 32:6 So Elihu son of Barakel the Buzite said£º "I am young in years, and you are old; that is why I was fearful, not daring to tell you what I know.
18Jb 32:7 I thought, 'Age should speak; advanced years should teach wisdom.'
18Jb 32:8 But it is the spirit in a man, the breath of the Almighty, that gives him understanding.
18Jb 32:9 It is not only the old who are wise, not only the aged who understand what is right.
18Jb 32:10 "Therefore I say£º Listen to me; I too will tell you what I know.
18Jb 32:11 I waited while you spoke, I listened to your reasoning; while you were searching for words,
18Jb 32:12 I gave you my full attention. But not one of you has proved Job wrong; none of you has answered his arguments.
18Jb 32:13 Do not say, 'We have found wisdom; let God refute him, not man.'
18Jb 32:14 But Job has not marshaled his words against me, and I will not answer him with your arguments.
18Jb 32:15 "They are dismayed and have no more to say; words have failed them.
18Jb 32:16 Must I wait, now that they are silent, now that they stand there with no reply?
18Jb 32:17 I too will have my say; I too will tell what I know.
18Jb 32:18 For I am full of words, and the spirit within me compels me;
18Jb 32:19 inside I am like bottled-up wine, like new wineskins ready to burst.
18Jb 32:20 I must speak and find relief; I must open my lips and reply.
18Jb 32:21 I will show partiality to no one, nor will I flatter any man;
18Jb 32:22 for if I were skilled in flattery, my Maker would soon take me away.
18Jb 33:1 "But now, Job, listen to my words; pay attention to everything I say.
18Jb 33:2 I am about to open my mouth; my words are on the tip of my tongue.
18Jb 33:3 My words come from an upright heart; my lips sincerely speak what I know.
18Jb 33:4 The Spirit of God has made me; the breath of the Almighty gives me life.
18Jb 33:5 Answer me then, if you can; prepare yourself and confront me.
18Jb 33:6 I am just like you before God; I too have been taken from clay.
18Jb 33:7 No fear of me should alarm you, nor should my hand be heavy upon you.
18Jb 33:8 "But you have said in my hearing--I heard the very words--
18Jb 33:9 'I am pure and without sin; I am clean and free from guilt.
18Jb 33:10 Yet God has found fault with me; he considers me his enemy.
18Jb 33:11 He fastens my feet in shackles; he keeps close watch on all my paths.'
18Jb 33:12 "But I tell you, in this you are not right, for God is greater than man.
18Jb 33:13 Why do you complain to him that he answers none of man's words?
18Jb 33:14 For God does speak--now one way, now another--though man may not perceive it.
18Jb 33:15 In a dream, in a vision of the night, when deep sleep falls on men as they slumber in their beds,
18Jb 33:16 he may speak in their ears and terrify them with warnings,
18Jb 33:17 to turn man from wrongdoing and keep him from pride,
18Jb 33:18 to preserve his soul from the pit, his life from perishing by the sword.
18Jb 33:19 Or a man may be chastened on a bed of pain with constant distress in his bones,
18Jb 33:20 so that his very being finds food repulsive and his soul loathes the choicest meal.
18Jb 33:21 His flesh wastes away to nothing, and his bones, once hidden, now stick out.
18Jb 33:22 His soul draws near to the pit, and his life to the messengers of death.
18Jb 33:23 "Yet if there is an angel on his side as a mediator, one out of a thousand, to tell a man what is right for him,
18Jb 33:24 to be gracious to him and say, 'Spare him from going down to the pit; I have found a ransom for him'--
18Jb 33:25 then his flesh is renewed like a child's; it is restored as in the days of his youth.
18Jb 33:26 He prays to God and finds favor with him, he sees God's face and shouts for joy; he is restored by God to his righteous state.
18Jb 33:27 Then he comes to men and says, 'I sinned, and perverted what was right, but I did not get what I deserved.
18Jb 33:28 He redeemed my soul from going down to the pit, and I will live to enjoy the light.'
18Jb 33:29 "God does all these things to a man--twice, even three times--
18Jb 33:30 to turn back his soul from the pit, that the light of life may shine on him.
18Jb 33:31 "Pay attention, Job, and listen to me; be silent, and I will speak.
18Jb 33:32 If you have anything to say, answer me; speak up, for I want you to be cleared.
18Jb 33:33 But if not, then listen to me; be silent, and I will teach you wisdom."
18Jb 34:1 Then Elihu said£º
18Jb 34:2 "Hear my words, you wise men; listen to me, you men of learning.
18Jb 34:3 For the ear tests words as the tongue tastes food.
18Jb 34:4 Let us discern for ourselves what is right; let us learn together what is good.
18Jb 34:5 "Job says, 'I am innocent, but God denies me justice.
18Jb 34:6 Although I am right, I am considered a liar; although I am guiltless, his arrow inflicts an incurable wound.'
18Jb 34:7 What man is like Job, who drinks scorn like water?
18Jb 34:8 He keeps company with evildoers; he associates with wicked men.
18Jb 34:9 For he says, 'It profits a man nothing when he tries to please God.'
18Jb 34:10 "So listen to me, you men of understanding. Far be it from God to do evil, from the Almighty to do wrong.
18Jb 34:11 He repays a man for what he has done; he brings upon him what his conduct deserves.
18Jb 34:12 It is unthinkable that God would do wrong, that the Almighty would pervert justice.
18Jb 34:13 Who appointed him over the earth? Who put him in charge of the whole world?
18Jb 34:14 If it were his intention and he withdrew his spirit and breath,
18Jb 34:15 all mankind would perish together and man would return to the dust.
18Jb 34:16 "If you have understanding, hear this; listen to what I say.
18Jb 34:17 Can he who hates justice govern? Will you condemn the just and mighty One?
18Jb 34:18 Is he not the One who says to kings, 'You are worthless,' and to nobles, 'You are wicked,'
18Jb 34:19 who shows no partiality to princes and does not favor the rich over the poor, for they are all the work of his hands?
18Jb 34:20 They die in an instant, in the middle of the night; the people are shaken and they pass away; the mighty are removed without human hand.
18Jb 34:21 "His eyes are on the ways of men; he sees their every step.
18Jb 34:22 There is no dark place, no deep shadow, where evildoers can hide.
18Jb 34:23 God has no need to examine men further, that they should come before him for judgment.
18Jb 34:24 Without inquiry he shatters the mighty and sets up others in their place.
18Jb 34:25 Because he takes note of their deeds, he overthrows them in the night and they are crushed.
18Jb 34:26 He punishes them for their wickedness where everyone can see them,
18Jb 34:27 because they turned from following him and had no regard for any of his ways.
18Jb 34:28 They caused the cry of the poor to come before him, so that he heard the cry of the needy.
18Jb 34:29 But if he remains silent, who can condemn him? If he hides his face, who can see him? Yet he is over man and nation alike,
18Jb 34:30 to keep a godless man from ruling, from laying snares for the people.
18Jb 34:31 "Suppose a man says to God, 'I am guilty but will offend no more.
18Jb 34:32 Teach me what I cannot see; if I have done wrong, I will not do so again.'
18Jb 34:33 Should God then reward you on your terms, when you refuse to repent? You must decide, not I; so tell me what you know.
18Jb 34:34 "Men of understanding declare, wise men who hear me say to me,
18Jb 34:35 'Job speaks without knowledge; his words lack insight.'
18Jb 34:36 Oh, that Job might be tested to the utmost for answering like a wicked man!
18Jb 34:37 To his sin he adds rebellion; scornfully he claps his hands among us and multiplies his words against God."
18Jb 35:1 Then Elihu said£º
18Jb 35:2 "Do you think this is just? You say, 'I will be cleared by God.'
18Jb 35:3 Yet you ask him, 'What profit is it to me, and what do I gain by not sinning?'
18Jb 35:4 "I would like to reply to you and to your friends with you.
18Jb 35:5 Look up at the heavens and see; gaze at the clouds so high above you.
18Jb 35:6 If you sin, how does that affect him? If your sins are many, what does that do to him?
18Jb 35:7 If you are righteous, what do you give to him, or what does he receive from your hand?
18Jb 35:8 Your wickedness affects only a man like yourself, and your righteousness only the sons of men.
18Jb 35:9 "Men cry out under a load of oppression; they plead for relief from the arm of the powerful.
18Jb 35:10 But no one says, 'Where is God my Maker, who gives songs in the night,
18Jb 35:11 who teaches more to us than to the beasts of the earth and makes us wiser than the birds of the air?'
18Jb 35:12 He does not answer when men cry out because of the arrogance of the wicked.
18Jb 35:13 Indeed, God does not listen to their empty plea; the Almighty pays no attention to it.
18Jb 35:14 How much less, then, will he listen when you say that you do not see him, that your case is before him and you must wait for him,
18Jb 35:15 and further, that his anger never punishes and he does not take the least notice of wickedness.
18Jb 35:16 So Job opens his mouth with empty talk; without knowledge he multiplies words."
18Jb 36:1 Elihu continued£º
18Jb 36:2 "Bear with me a little longer and I will show you that there is more to be said in God's behalf.
18Jb 36:3 I get my knowledge from afar; I will ascribe justice to my Maker.
18Jb 36:4 Be assured that my words are not false; one perfect in knowledge is with you.
18Jb 36:5 "God is mighty, but does not despise men; he is mighty, and firm in his purpose.
18Jb 36:6 He does not keep the wicked alive but gives the afflicted their rights.
18Jb 36:7 He does not take his eyes off the righteous; he enthrones them with kings and exalts them forever.
18Jb 36:8 But if men are bound in chains, held fast by cords of affliction,
18Jb 36:9 he tells them what they have done--that they have sinned arrogantly.
18Jb 36:10 He makes them listen to correction and commands them to repent of their evil.
18Jb 36:11 If they obey and serve him, they will spend the rest of their days in prosperity and their years in contentment.
18Jb 36:12 But if they do not listen, they will perish by the sword and die without knowledge.
18Jb 36:13 "The godless in heart harbor resentment; even when he fetters them, they do not cry for help.
18Jb 36:14 They die in their youth, among male prostitutes of the shrines.
18Jb 36:15 But those who suffer he delivers in their suffering; he speaks to them in their affliction.
18Jb 36:16 "He is wooing you from the jaws of distress to a spacious place free from restriction, to the comfort of your table laden with choice food.
18Jb 36:17 But now you are laden with the judgment due the wicked; judgment and justice have taken hold of you.
18Jb 36:18 Be careful that no one entices you by riches; do not let a large bribe turn you aside.
18Jb 36:19 Would your wealth or even all your mighty efforts sustain you so you would not be in distress?
18Jb 36:20 Do not long for the night, to drag people away from their homes.
18Jb 36:21 Beware of turning to evil, which you seem to prefer to affliction.
18Jb 36:22 "God is exalted in his power. Who is a teacher like him?
18Jb 36:23 Who has prescribed his ways for him, or said to him, 'You have done wrong'?
18Jb 36:24 Remember to extol his work, which men have praised in song.
18Jb 36:25 All mankind has seen it; men gaze on it from afar.
18Jb 36:26 How great is God--beyond our understanding! The number of his years is past finding out.
18Jb 36:27 "He draws up the drops of water, which distill as rain to the streams;
18Jb 36:28 the clouds pour down their moisture and abundant showers fall on mankind.
18Jb 36:29 Who can understand how he spreads out the clouds, how he thunders from his pavilion?
18Jb 36:30 See how he scatters his lightning about him, bathing the depths of the sea.
18Jb 36:31 This is the way he governs the nations and provides food in abundance.
18Jb 36:32 He fills his hands with lightning and commands it to strike its mark.
18Jb 36:33 His thunder announces the coming storm; even the cattle make known its approach.
18Jb 37:1 "At this my heart pounds and leaps from its place.
18Jb 37:2 Listen! Listen to the roar of his voice, to the rumbling that comes from his mouth.
18Jb 37:3 He unleashes his lightning beneath the whole heaven and sends it to the ends of the earth.
18Jb 37:4 After that comes the sound of his roar; he thunders with his majestic voice. When his voice resounds, he holds nothing back.
18Jb 37:5 God's voice thunders in marvelous ways; he does great things beyond our understanding.
18Jb 37:6 He says to the snow, 'Fall on the earth,' and to the rain shower, 'Be a mighty downpour.'
18Jb 37:7 So that all men he has made may know his work, he stops every man from his labor.
18Jb 37:8 The animals take cover; they remain in their dens.
18Jb 37:9 The tempest comes out from its chamber, the cold from the driving winds.
18Jb 37:10 The breath of God produces ice, and the broad waters become frozen.
18Jb 37:11 He loads the clouds with moisture; he scatters his lightning through them.
18Jb 37:12 At his direction they swirl around over the face of the whole earth to do whatever he commands them.
18Jb 37:13 He brings the clouds to punish men, or to water his earth and show his love.
18Jb 37:14 "Listen to this, Job; stop and consider God's wonders.
18Jb 37:15 Do you know how God controls the clouds and makes his lightning flash?
18Jb 37:16 Do you know how the clouds hang poised, those wonders of him who is perfect in knowledge?
18Jb 37:17 You who swelter in your clothes when the land lies hushed under the south wind,
18Jb 37:18 can you join him in spreading out the skies, hard as a mirror of cast bronze?
18Jb 37:19 "Tell us what we should say to him; we cannot draw up our case because of our darkness.
18Jb 37:20 Should he be told that I want to speak? Would any man ask to be swallowed up?
18Jb 37:21 Now no one can look at the sun, bright as it is in the skies after the wind has swept them clean.
18Jb 37:22 Out of the north he comes in golden splendor; God comes in awesome majesty.
18Jb 37:23 The Almighty is beyond our reach and exalted in power; in his justice and great righteousness, he does not oppress.
18Jb 37:24 Therefore, men revere him, for does he not have regard for all the wise in heart?"
18Jb 38:1 Then the LORD answered Job out of the storm. He said£º
18Jb 38:2 "Who is this that darkens my counsel with words without knowledge?
18Jb 38:3 Brace yourself like a man; I will question you, and you shall answer me.
18Jb 38:4 "Where were you when I laid the earth's foundation? Tell me, if you understand.
18Jb 38:5 Who marked off its dimensions? Surely you know! Who stretched a measuring line across it?
18Jb 38:6 On what were its footings set, or who laid its cornerstone--
18Jb 38:7 while the morning stars sang together and all the angels shouted for joy?
18Jb 38:8 "Who shut up the sea behind doors when it burst forth from the womb,
18Jb 38:9 when I made the clouds its garment and wrapped it in thick darkness,
18Jb 38:10 when I fixed limits for it and set its doors and bars in place,
18Jb 38:11 when I said, 'This far you may come and no farther; here is where your proud waves halt'?
18Jb 38:12 "Have you ever given orders to the morning, or shown the dawn its place,
18Jb 38:13 that it might take the earth by the edges and shake the wicked out of it?
18Jb 38:14 The earth takes shape like clay under a seal; its features stand out like those of a garment.
18Jb 38:15 The wicked are denied their light, and their upraised arm is broken.
18Jb 38:16 "Have you journeyed to the springs of the sea or walked in the recesses of the deep?
18Jb 38:17 Have the gates of death been shown to you? Have you seen the gates of the shadow of death?
18Jb 38:18 Have you comprehended the vast expanses of the earth? Tell me, if you know all this.
18Jb 38:19 "What is the way to the abode of light? And where does darkness reside?
18Jb 38:20 Can you take them to their places? Do you know the paths to their dwellings?
18Jb 38:21 Surely you know, for you were already born! You have lived so many years!
18Jb 38:22 "Have you entered the storehouses of the snow or seen the storehouses of the hail,
18Jb 38:23 which I reserve for times of trouble, for days of war and battle?
18Jb 38:24 What is the way to the place where the lightning is dispersed, or the place where the east winds are scattered over the earth?
18Jb 38:25 Who cuts a channel for the torrents of rain, and a path for the thunderstorm,
18Jb 38:26 to water a land where no man lives, a desert with no one in it,
18Jb 38:27 to satisfy a desolate wasteland and make it sprout with grass?
18Jb 38:28 Does the rain have a father? Who fathers the drops of dew?
18Jb 38:29 From whose womb comes the ice? Who gives birth to the frost from the heavens
18Jb 38:30 when the waters become hard as stone, when the surface of the deep is frozen?
18Jb 38:31 "Can you bind the beautiful Pleiades? Can you loose the cords of Orion?
18Jb 38:32 Can you bring forth the constellations in their seasons or lead out the Bear with its cubs?
18Jb 38:33 Do you know the laws of the heavens? Can you set up God'sdominion over the earth?
18Jb 38:34 "Can you raise your voice to the clouds and cover yourself with a flood of water?
18Jb 38:35 Do you send the lightning bolts on their way? Do they report to you, 'Here we are'?
18Jb 38:36 Who endowed the heart with wisdom or gave understanding to the mind?
18Jb 38:37 Who has the wisdom to count the clouds? Who can tip over the water jars of the heavens
18Jb 38:38 when the dust becomes hard and the clods of earth stick together?
18Jb 38:39 "Do you hunt the prey for the lioness and satisfy the hunger of the lions
18Jb 38:40 when they crouch in their dens or lie in wait in a thicket?
18Jb 38:41 Who provides food for the raven when its young cry out to God and wander about for lack of food?
18Jb 39:1 "Do you know when the mountain goats give birth? Do you watch when the doe bears her fawn?
18Jb 39:2 Do you count the months till they bear? Do you know the time they give birth?
18Jb 39:3 They crouch down and bring forth their young; their labor pains are ended.
18Jb 39:4 Their young thrive and grow strong in the wilds; they leave and do not return.
18Jb 39:5 "Who let the wild donkey go free? Who untied his ropes?
18Jb 39:6 I gave him the wasteland as his home, the salt flats as his habitat.
18Jb 39:7 He laughs at the commotion in the town; he does not hear a driver's shout.
18Jb 39:8 He ranges the hills for his pasture and searches for any green thing.
18Jb 39:9 "Will the wild ox consent to serve you? Will he stay by your manger at night?
18Jb 39:10 Can you hold him to the furrow with a harness? Will he till the valleys behind you?
18Jb 39:11 Will you rely on him for his great strength? Will you leave your heavy work to him?
18Jb 39:12 Can you trust him to bring in your grain and gather it to your threshing floor?
18Jb 39:13 "The wings of the ostrich flap joyfully, but they cannot compare with the pinions and feathers of the stork.
18Jb 39:14 She lays her eggs on the ground and lets them warm in the sand,
18Jb 39:15 unmindful that a foot may crush them, that some wild animal may trample them.
18Jb 39:16 She treats her young harshly, as if they were not hers; she cares not that her labor was in vain,
18Jb 39:17 for God did not endow her with wisdom or give her a share of good sense.
18Jb 39:18 Yet when she spreads her feathers to run, she laughs at horse and rider.
18Jb 39:19 "Do you give the horse his strength or clothe his neck with a flowing mane?
18Jb 39:20 Do you make him leap like a locust, striking terror with his proud snorting?
18Jb 39:21 He paws fiercely, rejoicing in his strength, and charges into the fray.
18Jb 39:22 He laughs at fear, afraid of nothing; he does not shy away from the sword.
18Jb 39:23 The quiver rattles against his side, along with the flashing spear and lance.
18Jb 39:24 In frenzied excitement he eats up the ground; he cannot stand still when the trumpet sounds.
18Jb 39:25 At the blast of the trumpet he snorts, 'Aha!' He catches the scent of battle from afar, the shout of commanders and the battle cry.
18Jb 39:26 "Does the hawk take flight by your wisdom and spread his wings toward the south?
18Jb 39:27 Does the eagle soar at your command and build his nest on high?
18Jb 39:28 He dwells on a cliff and stays there at night; a rocky crag is his stronghold.
18Jb 39:29 From there he seeks out his food; his eyes detect it from afar.
18Jb 39:30 His young ones feast on blood, and where the slain are, there is he."
18Jb 40:1 The LORD said to Job£º
18Jb 40:2 "Will the one who contends with the Almighty correct him? Let him who accuses God answer him!"
18Jb 40:3 Then Job answered the LORD£º
18Jb 40:4 "I am unworthy--how can I reply to you? I put my hand over my mouth.
18Jb 40:5 I spoke once, but I have no answer--twice, but I will say no more."
18Jb 40:6 Then the LORD spoke to Job out of the storm£º
18Jb 40:7 "Brace yourself like a man; I will question you, and you shall answer me.
18Jb 40:8 "Would you discredit my justice? Would you condemn me to justify yourself?
18Jb 40:9 Do you have an arm like God's, and can your voice thunder like his?
18Jb 40:10 Then adorn yourself with glory and splendor, and clothe yourself in honor and majesty.
18Jb 40:11 Unleash the fury of your wrath, look at every proud man and bring him low,
18Jb 40:12 look at every proud man and humble him, crush the wicked where they stand.
18Jb 40:13 Bury them all in the dust together; shroud their faces in the grave.
18Jb 40:14 Then I myself will admit to you that your own right hand can save you.
18Jb 40:15 "Look at the behemoth, which I made along with you and which feeds on grass like an ox.
18Jb 40:16 What strength he has in his loins, what power in the muscles of his belly!
18Jb 40:17 His tail sways like a cedar; the sinews of his thighs are close-knit.
18Jb 40:18 His bones are tubes of bronze, his limbs like rods of iron.
18Jb 40:19 He ranks first among the works of God, yet his Maker can approach him with his sword.
18Jb 40:20 The hills bring him their produce, and all the wild animals play nearby.
18Jb 40:21 Under the lotus plants he lies, hidden among the reeds in the marsh.
18Jb 40:22 The lotuses conceal him in their shadow; the poplars by the stream surround him.
18Jb 40:23 When the river rages, he is not alarmed; he is secure, though the Jordan should surge against his mouth.
18Jb 40:24 Can anyone capture him by the eyes, or trap him and pierce his nose?
18Jb 41:1 "Can you pull in the leviathan with a fishhook or tie down his tongue with a rope?
18Jb 41:2 Can you put a cord through his nose or pierce his jaw with a hook?
18Jb 41:3 Will he keep begging you for mercy? Will he speak to you with gentle words?
18Jb 41:4 Will he make an agreement with you for you to take him as your slave for life?
18Jb 41:5 Can you make a pet of him like a bird or put him on a leash for your girls?
18Jb 41:6 Will traders barter for him? Will they divide him up among the merchants?
18Jb 41:7 Can you fill his hide with harpoons or his head with fishing spears?
18Jb 41:8 If you lay a hand on him, you will remember the struggle and never do it again!
18Jb 41:9 Any hope of subduing him is false; the mere sight of him is overpowering.
18Jb 41:10 No one is fierce enough to rouse him. Who then is able to stand against me?
18Jb 41:11 Who has a claim against me that I must pay? Everything under heaven belongs to me.
18Jb 41:12 "I will not fail to speak of his limbs, his strength and his graceful form.
18Jb 41:13 Who can strip off his outer coat? Who would approach him with a bridle?
18Jb 41:14 Who dares open the doors of his mouth, ringed about with his fearsome teeth?
18Jb 41:15 His back has rows of shields tightly sealed together;
18Jb 41:16 each is so close to the next that no air can pass between.
18Jb 41:17 They are joined fast to one another; they cling together and cannot be parted.
18Jb 41:18 His snorting throws out flashes of light; his eyes are like the rays of dawn.
18Jb 41:19 Firebrands stream from his mouth; sparks of fire shoot out.
18Jb 41:20 Smoke pours from his nostrils as from a boiling pot over a fire of reeds.
18Jb 41:21 His breath sets coals ablaze, and flames dart from his mouth.
18Jb 41:22 Strength resides in his neck; dismay goes before him.
18Jb 41:23 The folds of his flesh are tightly joined; they are firm and immovable.
18Jb 41:24 His chest is hard as rock, hard as a lower millstone.
18Jb 41:25 When he rises up, the mighty are terrified; they retreat before his thrashing.
18Jb 41:26 The sword that reaches him has no effect, nor does the spear or the dart or the javelin.
18Jb 41:27 Iron he treats like straw and bronze like rotten wood.
18Jb 41:28 Arrows do not make him flee; slingstones are like chaff to him.
18Jb 41:29 A club seems to him but a piece of straw; he laughs at the rattling of the lance.
18Jb 41:30 His undersides are jagged potsherds, leaving a trail in the mud like a threshing sledge.
18Jb 41:31 He makes the depths churn like a boiling caldron and stirs up the sea like a pot of ointment.
18Jb 41:32 Behind him he leaves a glistening wake; one would think the deep had white hair.
18Jb 41:33 Nothing on earth is his equal--a creature without fear.
18Jb 41:34 He looks down on all that are haughty; he is king over all that are proud."
18Jb 42:1 Then Job replied to the LORD£º
18Jb 42:2 "I know that you can do all things; no plan of yours can be thwarted.
18Jb 42:3 You asked,'Who is this that obscures my counsel without knowledge?' Surely I spoke of things I did not understand, things too wonderful for me to know.
18Jb 42:4 "You said,'Listen now, and I will speak; I will question you, and you shall answer me.'
18Jb 42:5 My ears had heard of you but now my eyes have seen you.
18Jb 42:6 Therefore I despise myself and repent in dust and ashes."
18Jb 42:7 After the LORD had said these things to Job, he said to Eliphaz the Temanite, "I am angry with you and your two friends, because you have not spoken of me what is right, as my servant Job has.
18Jb 42:8 So now take seven bulls and seven rams and go to my servant Job and sacrifice a burnt offering for yourselves. My servant Job will pray for you, and I will accept his prayer and not deal with you according to your folly. You have not spoken of me what is right, as my servant Job has."
18Jb 42:9 So Eliphaz the Temanite, Bildad the Shuhite and Zophar the Naamathite did what the LORD told them; and the LORD accepted Job's prayer.
18Jb 42:10 After Job had prayed for his friends, the LORD made him prosperous again and gave him twice as much as he had before.
18Jb 42:11 All his brothers and sisters and everyone who had known him before came and ate with him in his house. They comforted and consoled him over all the trouble the LORD had brought upon him, and each one gave him a piece of silver and a gold ring.
18Jb 42:12 The LORD blessed the latter part of Job's life more than the first. He had fourteen thousand sheep, six thousand camels, a thousand yoke of oxen and a thousand donkeys.
18Jb 42:13 And he also had seven sons and three daughters.
18Jb 42:14 The first daughter he named Jemimah, the second Keziah and the third Keren-Happuch.
18Jb 42:15 Nowhere in all the land were there found women as beautiful as Job's daughters, and their father granted them an inheritance along with their brothers.
18Jb 42:16 After this, Job lived a hundred and forty years; he saw his children and their children to the fourth generation.
18Jb 42:17 And so he died, old and full of years.
